WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.637 --> 00:00:07.220
SHEILA BOWMAN: Good
morning, everyone.

00:00:07.220 --> 00:00:08.350
My name is Sheila Bowman.

00:00:08.350 --> 00:00:11.200
I'm with the Monterey Bay
Aquarium Seafood Watch program.

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:13.920
We're extremely pleased to
be here and have a chance

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:16.740
to thank you, but also
to meet each one of you

00:00:16.740 --> 00:00:19.990
Googlers, and, of course,
hopefully encourage you

00:00:19.990 --> 00:00:22.490
and invite you to join us down
at the Monterey Bay Aquarium,

00:00:22.490 --> 00:00:24.660
when you have free time.

00:00:24.660 --> 00:00:27.420
All the programs that we do
really depend on great folks

00:00:27.420 --> 00:00:29.330
like you coming in
and supporting us.

00:00:29.330 --> 00:00:31.413
And one of our programs
that we're especially here

00:00:31.413 --> 00:00:34.140
to talk about today is, of
course, our sustainable seafood

00:00:34.140 --> 00:00:35.120
program.

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:37.240
And I'm going to
take this opportunity

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:41.960
to welcome and introduce to
those who don't know Chef Rick

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:45.210
Moonen, who's come to us this
morning from Las Vegas, where

00:00:45.210 --> 00:00:47.270
he has two successful
restaurants.

00:00:47.270 --> 00:00:50.820
And really, beyond
that, I think everyone

00:00:50.820 --> 00:00:53.420
who knows Rick knows he
has a world of experience

00:00:53.420 --> 00:00:57.910
beyond that, from TV--
"Top Chef Masters" program.

00:00:57.910 --> 00:01:00.340
He travels the
world-- in my opinion

00:01:00.340 --> 00:01:03.480
is the foremost chef who is
speaking out on sustainable

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:07.060
seafood issues, educating
himself, engaging, really,

00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:11.670
at the level of fish farmers
who don't know how to improve

00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:14.490
and want to improve, all the
way through to these premium

00:01:14.490 --> 00:01:15.380
products.

00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:17.350
The folks who have made
this conversion, who

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:20.530
have done great work, who
are providing sustainable

00:01:20.530 --> 00:01:23.300
seafood-- helping promote
them, so that all of us

00:01:23.300 --> 00:01:25.960
can enjoy this great
fish that's come so far.

00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:29.350
And in so many cases, we have
environmental heroes out there,

00:01:29.350 --> 00:01:32.570
where we can support them and
still enjoy delicious food.

00:01:32.570 --> 00:01:36.140
So I think I'm going to just
go ahead and turn things over

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:38.970
to Rick, 'cause I know he's
got to get the lentils started.

00:01:38.970 --> 00:01:42.427
So please, everybody--
Seafood Watch spokesperson,

00:01:42.427 --> 00:01:43.760
and my good friend, Rick Moonen.

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:45.510
RICK MOONEN: Thanks,
Sheila, that's great.

00:01:45.510 --> 00:01:48.500
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:48.500 --> 00:01:49.990
What a tremendous
privilege, to be

00:01:49.990 --> 00:01:51.330
able to be standing in
front of all of you.

00:01:51.330 --> 00:01:53.970
Just because-- not only just
of the mentality of the Google

00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:56.870
campus-- and Google world,
I might as well say,

00:01:56.870 --> 00:01:59.160
but it's your generation.

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:00.050
It's you.

00:02:00.050 --> 00:02:01.680
You are the thinkers.

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:03.170
You are the future.

00:02:03.170 --> 00:02:06.100
I've been focused
on sustainability

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:07.740
for my entire career.

00:02:07.740 --> 00:02:10.090
I graduated culinary
school in the '70s.

00:02:10.090 --> 00:02:10.800
1978.

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:11.680
First in my class.

00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:12.180
Yay!

00:02:12.180 --> 00:02:15.710
But I worked with some great
chefs that instilled in me

00:02:15.710 --> 00:02:18.525
an integrity, a
respect, a connection,

00:02:18.525 --> 00:02:20.930
and an understanding
about our environment.

00:02:20.930 --> 00:02:22.940
Healthy environment
equals healthy food.

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:28.810
Better, healthy environment
makes tasty, delicious,

00:02:28.810 --> 00:02:30.607
nutritious, real food.

00:02:30.607 --> 00:02:32.940
And the biggest problem,
today, that we're faced-- well,

00:02:32.940 --> 00:02:34.940
not the biggest-- but one
of them-- one of many,

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:37.720
unfortunately-- is that
the food that we consume

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:39.862
is ofttimes so processed
that our bodies don't even

00:02:39.862 --> 00:02:40.820
see it as food anymore.

00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:42.450
It doesn't recognize it.

00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:45.020
And that's when immunity
systems start to break down,

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:46.710
and all kinds of stuff happens.

00:02:46.710 --> 00:02:49.000
That's a whole nother
topic of discussion.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:50.750
But it's just something
I want to open up,

00:02:50.750 --> 00:02:53.645
because real food
equals healthy-- health.

00:02:53.645 --> 00:02:54.770
You're going to be healthy.

00:02:54.770 --> 00:02:56.330
Every atom of your
body is a result

00:02:56.330 --> 00:02:58.038
of something you've
consumed or something

00:02:58.038 --> 00:02:59.440
you've come in contact with.

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:03.430
So let's be a little bit
more connected to that food--

00:03:03.430 --> 00:03:04.500
to that source.

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:06.480
And that's really about
the responsibility

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:08.230
of how I define sustainability.

00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:10.720
Sustaining, keeping--
making sure there's

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:13.310
enough for tomorrow,
for tomorrow's dinner,

00:03:13.310 --> 00:03:15.200
for the next generation--
your children,

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:18.330
yourselves, and everything
else, going on down the line.

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:21.025
Without putting our toys
away at the end of the night,

00:03:21.025 --> 00:03:22.650
we're not going to
be able to have them

00:03:22.650 --> 00:03:23.567
tomorrow to play with.

00:03:23.567 --> 00:03:24.066
Right?

00:03:24.066 --> 00:03:25.060
It's pretty simple.

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:27.680
So I'm going to do that through
a cooking demonstration.

00:03:27.680 --> 00:03:29.263
But really, the
opportunity is to have

00:03:29.263 --> 00:03:30.507
this ongoing discussion.

00:03:30.507 --> 00:03:32.090
And if I can change
the way you think,

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:34.160
a little bit, today,
then I've succeeded.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:37.490
If I can connect you to a
great source of information

00:03:37.490 --> 00:03:40.040
to help you along, as you're,
like, I got a little bit of it,

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:41.300
but I need more,
then we're going

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:43.424
to talk about Seafood Watch,
and what they've done,

00:03:43.424 --> 00:03:44.870
and what they do
every single day.

00:03:44.870 --> 00:03:47.560
They've got a team
of people in Monterey

00:03:47.560 --> 00:03:51.570
that are connecting to a
crazy network of scientists,

00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:54.590
environmental groups, people
that are-- government-- that

00:03:54.590 --> 00:03:58.970
are measuring and taking census
of different species of fish

00:03:58.970 --> 00:03:59.640
and stuff.

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:03.370
Measuring their potential
to be able to reproduce

00:04:03.370 --> 00:04:06.140
enough to produce what we
want for the following year.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:07.750
A lot goes into this.

00:04:07.750 --> 00:04:10.262
And I'm not here to
scare you about it.

00:04:10.262 --> 00:04:11.720
But I hope that
you'll be motivated

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:13.700
to know more about your
food at the end of this.

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:14.050
Jeez!

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:14.841
I didn't know that!

00:04:14.841 --> 00:04:15.800
All right!

00:04:15.800 --> 00:04:16.660
Now I know more.

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:18.160
So let's get the
lentils started.

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:19.920
Anyway, what I'm going
to show you today

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:23.004
is I'm choosing a-- OK, so how
do I define sustainability?

00:04:23.004 --> 00:04:24.920
We're going to do that
when the lentils start.

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:28.605
Because these lentils-- brown
or green lentils are the lentils

00:04:28.605 --> 00:04:29.730
that you want to work with.

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:31.729
All those other colored
lentils are real pretty,

00:04:31.729 --> 00:04:32.780
but they turn to mush.

00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:33.730
They just do.

00:04:33.730 --> 00:04:37.040
So I'm just going to put some
cold water on some dry lentils.

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:38.930
You don't have to presoak them.

00:04:38.930 --> 00:04:42.950
It's not necessarily
a requirement.

00:04:42.950 --> 00:04:44.760
As a matter of fact, I never do.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:48.470
I just put cold water on the
fire, bring it up slowly,

00:04:48.470 --> 00:04:50.480
simmer it very, very gently.

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:52.790
And then, towards the end,
I'll season it with salt.

00:04:52.790 --> 00:04:54.730
If you salt it in
the very beginning,

00:04:54.730 --> 00:04:57.180
it has a tendency to
take longer to cook,

00:04:57.180 --> 00:04:58.370
be more uneven, et cetera.

00:04:58.370 --> 00:04:59.800
So that's Lentils 101.

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:00.300
Yay.

00:05:00.300 --> 00:05:01.810
We got that out of the way.

00:05:01.810 --> 00:05:06.430
Another thing, because I am
in love with Moroccan places,

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:06.930
right now.

00:05:06.930 --> 00:05:07.880
Indian spices.

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:11.550
I think-- what's the movie? "100
Foot Journey," or something?

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:12.310
What is it called?

00:05:12.310 --> 00:05:13.670
How many people have seen that?

00:05:13.670 --> 00:05:14.550
It's a cool movie.

00:05:14.550 --> 00:05:15.966
I mean, the coolest
part of it was

00:05:15.966 --> 00:05:19.260
when the guy pulled out this box
of jars, of mixtures and spices

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:19.926
from his mother.

00:05:19.926 --> 00:05:21.340
He's like-- [SNIFF].

00:05:21.340 --> 00:05:23.020
And the guy ended up, you know,
with a three-star Michelin

00:05:23.020 --> 00:05:23.540
restaurant.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:24.920
That blew my mind.

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:28.310
It's that depth of flavor
that we're kind of going for.

00:05:28.310 --> 00:05:30.860
It's the new
palette of intrigue.

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:33.412
It's the depth-- the smell--
turmeric-- ooh, really good!

00:05:33.412 --> 00:05:35.370
Turmeric is good because
it's anti-inflammatory

00:05:35.370 --> 00:05:37.600
and it helps get rid
of all the pains.

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:38.990
Food does that.

00:05:38.990 --> 00:05:40.790
Food can and always
will do that.

00:05:40.790 --> 00:05:46.240
It'll help solve 90% of the
concerns and health issues.

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:48.290
My opinion, OK.

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:49.940
So how do we go about that?

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:52.047
Take everything that
starts with a C,

00:05:52.047 --> 00:05:54.380
in your whole spice counter,
and that's pretty much what

00:05:54.380 --> 00:05:55.546
you're going to end up with.

00:05:55.546 --> 00:05:56.950
Coriander.

00:05:56.950 --> 00:05:57.970
Coriander seeds.

00:05:57.970 --> 00:06:00.160
Also, if you planted that
in the ground, what would

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:01.480
it grow up into?

00:06:01.480 --> 00:06:02.160
Cilantro.

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:02.840
That's correct.

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:03.980
I'll help you out.

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:04.480
OK.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:05.980
This is cumin.

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:08.030
Very deep, very
rich, very earthy,

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:11.320
very delic-- um-- widely used.

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:12.570
Many, many different cuisines.

00:06:12.570 --> 00:06:15.920
You're going to see it from
Greek, Mediterranean, Indian,

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:17.396
Moroccan.

00:06:17.396 --> 00:06:18.544
Cumin.

00:06:18.544 --> 00:06:20.960
This begins with an F, so we're
not going to go there yet.

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:22.600
These are cloves-- whole cloves.

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:27.090
Very oily, very deep, lot
of, um-- well, cloves.

00:06:27.090 --> 00:06:27.590
You know?

00:06:27.590 --> 00:06:30.090
It's what you-- they stick them
in ham when they roast them.

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:31.680
It's got a real
distinctive flavor.

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:32.830
So you only want
a couple of those,

00:06:32.830 --> 00:06:34.090
because that's very strong.

00:06:34.090 --> 00:06:35.890
This-- cardamom.

00:06:35.890 --> 00:06:36.816
Cardamom.

00:06:36.816 --> 00:06:37.940
Really, really interesting.

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:38.920
You've got green,
you've got black,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:39.250
you've got different ones.

00:06:39.250 --> 00:06:40.710
There's little seeds inside.

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:42.740
We use the whole
green cardamom when

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:46.270
we're making this
particular spice blend.

00:06:46.270 --> 00:06:49.590
And then-- so that's
everything with a C. Coriander,

00:06:49.590 --> 00:06:54.995
cumin-- not-- yeah-- coriander,
cumin, cardamom, and cloves.

00:06:54.995 --> 00:06:57.256
And then we get some
fennel, because we need

00:06:57.256 --> 00:06:58.710
a little F in there, I guess.

00:06:58.710 --> 00:06:59.510
Fennel.

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:00.770
You can add cinnamon in there.

00:07:00.770 --> 00:07:03.610
I'll often use turmeric--
you can add to it.

00:07:03.610 --> 00:07:05.920
And then you're starting to
go into like a curry style.

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:07.503
This isn't so much
like a curry style.

00:07:07.503 --> 00:07:09.520
This is going to be
based on some heat.

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:10.270
I want some spice.

00:07:10.270 --> 00:07:12.919
So, in order to get those
flavors out of there,

00:07:12.919 --> 00:07:13.710
I want to toast it.

00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:15.510
So that's why I'm
putting it in a dry pan.

00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:16.980
I have it on a medium heat.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:18.730
And I want to toast them.

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:20.530
Difference between a
piece of white bread,

00:07:20.530 --> 00:07:22.370
stick it in this little
machine, push down the thing,

00:07:22.370 --> 00:07:23.310
pops out toast.

00:07:23.310 --> 00:07:26.240
Big difference; same product.

00:07:26.240 --> 00:07:27.560
Kind of the same idea, here.

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:27.820
Right?

00:07:27.820 --> 00:07:28.694
You want to get the--

00:07:28.694 --> 00:07:31.557
And you're going to start
to smell the aroma--

00:07:31.557 --> 00:07:32.556
the aromatics out of it.

00:07:32.556 --> 00:07:33.930
So I'm keeping it
simple to five,

00:07:33.930 --> 00:07:36.620
but you can put up to 10
different spices in there.

00:07:36.620 --> 00:07:39.890
Good base, what I
just showed you.

00:07:39.890 --> 00:07:41.180
Lentils are cooking.

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:44.029
And I'm going to get
back to sustainability

00:07:44.029 --> 00:07:44.820
while this happens.

00:07:44.820 --> 00:07:46.600
This had to start
real soon, because it

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:48.690
takes a little bit of time.

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:51.090
Do not participate in
the activity that brings

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:53.900
a species to an extinction.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:55.360
So important.

00:07:55.360 --> 00:07:56.720
Ecosystem.

00:07:56.720 --> 00:07:59.180
Everything works in
conjunction with each other.

00:07:59.180 --> 00:08:02.950
Every living thing on
our planet plays a role.

00:08:02.950 --> 00:08:03.620
It was put here.

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:07.620
We didn't invent the plants or
any animals that are on here.

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:11.790
They all have a function
that helps the earth

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:13.540
stay healthy and go around.

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:15.550
You would never think
of taking something out

00:08:15.550 --> 00:08:17.925
of your car engine-- driving
down the highway and saying,

00:08:17.925 --> 00:08:18.970
"Hmm, you know?

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:20.577
I'm just going to
pull something out."

00:08:20.577 --> 00:08:22.160
And expect the engine
to run the same.

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:23.190
It would not.

00:08:23.190 --> 00:08:24.600
That's ridiculous.

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:29.640
Yet, if we allow something
to fall out of the ecosystem,

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:30.930
then we create an imbalance.

00:08:30.930 --> 00:08:33.003
An imbalance, then we
have to try to repair.

00:08:33.003 --> 00:08:34.669
You try to repair it,
you overrepair it.

00:08:34.669 --> 00:08:35.460
It's oversteering.

00:08:35.460 --> 00:08:36.418
It's all over the road.

00:08:36.418 --> 00:08:37.590
You can't do it.

00:08:37.590 --> 00:08:39.360
Study nature.

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:40.200
Emulate it.

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:41.664
Respect it.

00:08:41.664 --> 00:08:42.580
Earth will be healthy.

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:43.700
Environment will be healthy.

00:08:43.700 --> 00:08:44.230
We'll be healthy.

00:08:44.230 --> 00:08:44.730
OK?

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:45.750
I know I've repeated it.

00:08:45.750 --> 00:08:46.640
I'm not going to
bring it up again,

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:47.848
except maybe four more times.

00:08:47.848 --> 00:08:49.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:50.220
OK.

00:08:50.220 --> 00:08:52.870
So intriguing spice mix.

00:08:52.870 --> 00:08:54.280
Lentils.

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:56.502
I'll explain alternatives
to lentils, too.

00:08:56.502 --> 00:08:57.960
You know, a lot of
times, I'll just

00:08:57.960 --> 00:08:59.480
do what I call
"cauliflower rice."

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:00.290
You know what that is?

00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:01.590
You take a box grater,
you take a whole head

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:03.312
of raw cauliflower, and you
just-- [SCRAPING SOUNDS]

00:09:03.312 --> 00:09:04.830
--and just saute
it really quick.

00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:05.520
Boom.

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:07.810
Instantaneous,
gluten-free, grain-free,

00:09:07.810 --> 00:09:10.210
whatever free you want to
go down-- whatever road

00:09:10.210 --> 00:09:13.760
is floating your
boat at that moment.

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:16.340
There's really great vegetables
that help you to do that.

00:09:16.340 --> 00:09:16.840
OK.

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:21.640
I want to make, here, a harissa
sauce, or a fiery-hot tomato

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:22.690
sauce.

00:09:22.690 --> 00:09:26.830
Because somehow
vinegar-- acidity--

00:09:26.830 --> 00:09:30.740
works really, really,
really well with seafood.

00:09:30.740 --> 00:09:33.250
Take a piece of fish,
put it in a pan, cook it.

00:09:33.250 --> 00:09:34.846
What's the first
thing you need to do?

