00:28:28.090 --> 00:28:30.350
And I'm going to
pulse it, in a second,

00:28:30.350 --> 00:28:34.070
with my little handheld blender.

00:28:34.070 --> 00:28:35.360
That's heating up.

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:36.140
That's really hot.

00:28:36.140 --> 00:28:36.960
That's good.

00:28:36.960 --> 00:28:37.460
All right.

00:28:37.460 --> 00:28:44.330
So a slick of oil into the
pan, to keep it from sticking.

00:28:44.330 --> 00:28:46.520
Skin side down, because I'm
going to serve the skin.

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:47.270
I want the skin.

00:28:47.270 --> 00:28:47.925
The skin gets crispy.

00:28:47.925 --> 00:28:48.424
[SIZZLE]

00:28:48.424 --> 00:28:51.010
Hear that noise?

00:28:51.010 --> 00:28:52.011
That's-- that's like.

00:28:52.011 --> 00:28:52.510
I like.

00:28:52.510 --> 00:28:53.112
I likee.

00:28:53.112 --> 00:28:54.070
That's making me happy.

00:28:54.070 --> 00:28:56.040
And you see,
immediately, I do that?

00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:58.160
That's to make sure
it's not sticking.

00:28:58.160 --> 00:28:58.660
OK?

00:28:58.660 --> 00:28:59.451
We're not sticking.

00:28:59.451 --> 00:28:59.951
Yay!

00:28:59.951 --> 00:29:01.992
Because that's a pain in
the neck when it sticks.

00:29:01.992 --> 00:29:04.660
If it sticks, you kind
of leave it for a minute.

00:29:04.660 --> 00:29:06.230
Let it form a crust.

00:29:06.230 --> 00:29:06.820
Right?

00:29:06.820 --> 00:29:08.736
You can even-- if the
fish is so fresh that it

00:29:08.736 --> 00:29:11.520
starts to curl up, stop it.

00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:14.540
Just come down on it, a
little bit, with a spatula,

00:29:14.540 --> 00:29:18.570
to kind of fuse the skin
with the hot surface.

00:29:18.570 --> 00:29:19.070
All right?

00:29:19.070 --> 00:29:21.950
That fish is going
to cook, well, I'd

00:29:21.950 --> 00:29:24.047
say 90% of the way
on the skin side.

00:29:24.047 --> 00:29:26.380
I'll flip it over, for a
second, and just call it a day.

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:32.260
While that's cooking, I'm
going to puree my tomato

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:35.135
sauce by just--

00:29:35.135 --> 00:29:37.260
SHEILA BOWMAN: So, Rick,
shall we talk a little bit

00:29:37.260 --> 00:29:39.310
about fish diversity?

00:29:39.310 --> 00:29:42.310
How many people have
had trout before?

00:29:42.310 --> 00:29:43.169
Excellent!

00:29:43.169 --> 00:29:43.960
Really outstanding.

00:29:43.960 --> 00:29:46.210
Have you had it here at work,
or have you mostly-- has

00:29:46.210 --> 00:29:47.960
anyone cooked it at home?

00:29:47.960 --> 00:29:48.520
Really good.

00:29:48.520 --> 00:29:50.686
I think one of things that's
kind of fun about trout

00:29:50.686 --> 00:29:52.350
is you can also
do it whole fish.

00:29:52.350 --> 00:29:55.020
Kind of stuff it, and that
whole fish preparation.

00:29:55.020 --> 00:29:57.170
Super easy, super flavorful.

00:29:57.170 --> 00:30:00.620
It's kind of another new
trend in the way people

00:30:00.620 --> 00:30:01.500
are looking at fish.

00:30:01.500 --> 00:30:05.110
But lots of people are
not familiar with trout.

00:30:05.110 --> 00:30:07.430
So what other fish
are you guys eating?

00:30:07.430 --> 00:30:09.670
What kind of diversity
is in your diet?

00:30:09.670 --> 00:30:12.380
And Rick, I think
one of the things

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:16.220
we know is that salmon, shrimp,
and tuna are our top three

00:30:16.220 --> 00:30:17.530
seafoods in this country.

00:30:17.530 --> 00:30:21.820
And it's like 80% of the fish
we eat are those three fish.

00:30:21.820 --> 00:30:23.840
So one of the things
that we have to know,

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:25.491
when it comes to
sustainability, is

00:30:25.491 --> 00:30:27.490
we've got to diversify
our diet, because there's

00:30:27.490 --> 00:30:30.910
no way seven billion people can
live on three species of fish

00:30:30.910 --> 00:30:31.865
around the world.

00:30:31.865 --> 00:30:34.430
So trout's a great add.

00:30:34.430 --> 00:30:36.320
Crab's a great add.

00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:38.600
We have a new
group of fisheries,

00:30:38.600 --> 00:30:40.060
here on the Pacific
coast, which is

00:30:40.060 --> 00:30:43.720
all of our rockfish,
petrale sole, sand dabs.

00:30:43.720 --> 00:30:45.940
Those are all moved onto
our yellow and green list

00:30:45.940 --> 00:30:46.760
at Seafood Watch.

00:30:46.760 --> 00:30:48.370
They're great choices.

00:30:48.370 --> 00:30:52.200
So I think it's kind of
the era of weird fish.

00:30:52.200 --> 00:30:54.420
Sometimes people are calling
it "trash fish"-- fish

00:30:54.420 --> 00:30:56.790
that didn't have a
lot of financial value

00:30:56.790 --> 00:30:59.290
to fishermen, even two,
three, four years ago.

00:30:59.290 --> 00:31:02.780
But nowadays, chefs like
Rick are picking them up,

00:31:02.780 --> 00:31:06.410
making them into, like,
real shining-star dishes.

00:31:06.410 --> 00:31:09.640
And you start to
see different fish

00:31:09.640 --> 00:31:12.889
on menus than just kind
of the old standards.

00:31:12.889 --> 00:31:14.680
RICK MOONEN: Step
outside your comfort zone

00:31:14.680 --> 00:31:16.240
is what Sheila's saying.

00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:17.800
You know, generally
speaking, I think

00:31:17.800 --> 00:31:20.250
people eat mostly about three or
four different species of fish,

00:31:20.250 --> 00:31:20.833
and that's it.

00:31:20.833 --> 00:31:23.130
Eat something that you
haven't eaten before.

00:31:23.130 --> 00:31:24.820
Give a break to that species.

00:31:24.820 --> 00:31:27.600
We love single species to death.

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:31.320
We just consume them
until they're problematic.

00:31:31.320 --> 00:31:34.210
When there's so many other
things that are available.

00:31:34.210 --> 00:31:40.880
Chefs are dying to work with a
more diverse pantry or kitchen

00:31:40.880 --> 00:31:44.320
or refrigerator--
ocean products.

00:31:44.320 --> 00:31:44.820
All right.

00:31:44.820 --> 00:31:46.620
Here, this is just water.

00:31:46.620 --> 00:31:48.000
Put a pinch of salt in there.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:52.170
I'm going to shake some butter
into there until it emulsifies.

00:31:52.170 --> 00:31:54.572
And then I'm going to
reheat my lentils in there.

00:31:54.572 --> 00:31:56.280
And then we're pretty
much ready to rock.

00:31:56.280 --> 00:31:57.670
What I'm going to
need is some cilantro,

00:31:57.670 --> 00:32:00.050
if you guys got some cilantro
for garnish, in a second.

00:32:00.050 --> 00:32:03.350
So you'll notice, as
you're cooking, the sides.

00:32:03.350 --> 00:32:05.960
Look at the sides while
something's cooking.

00:32:05.960 --> 00:32:08.385
You see the bubbles
happening, there?

00:32:08.385 --> 00:32:10.620
That means that
everything's touching

00:32:10.620 --> 00:32:11.784
the surface of the pan.

00:32:11.784 --> 00:32:13.200
If there's no
bubbles on one side,

00:32:13.200 --> 00:32:16.900
it's probably because of it
kind of humped up or something.

00:32:16.900 --> 00:32:18.580
So I see that it's
starting to brown.

00:32:18.580 --> 00:32:22.460
I see that the sides of it
are starting to turn whiter.

00:32:22.460 --> 00:32:23.506
Right?

00:32:23.506 --> 00:32:24.880
How do I know if
fish is cooking?

00:32:24.880 --> 00:32:25.550
How do I know?

00:32:25.550 --> 00:32:26.370
Oh, I'm so scared!

00:32:26.370 --> 00:32:27.660
It's so expensive
to cook so quick.

00:32:27.660 --> 00:32:28.310
It's going to get dry.

00:32:28.310 --> 00:32:28.810
Aaiigh!

00:32:28.810 --> 00:32:29.370
No.

00:32:29.370 --> 00:32:30.310
Just look at it.

00:32:30.310 --> 00:32:31.900
You've cooked an egg.

00:32:31.900 --> 00:32:33.470
You've popped an egg into a pan.

00:32:33.470 --> 00:32:36.880
You've seen the egg white
go from clear to white.

00:32:36.880 --> 00:32:38.260
That's what happens
with protein.

00:32:38.260 --> 00:32:39.820
So that's turning
from clear-- which

00:32:39.820 --> 00:32:41.910
is kind of the middle,
still-- to white.

00:32:41.910 --> 00:32:44.930
So that fish is just about
ready to rock and roll.

00:32:44.930 --> 00:32:46.230
I'm just going to flip it over.

00:32:46.230 --> 00:32:46.730
Right?

00:32:46.730 --> 00:32:49.970
I've got a nice
little light brown.

00:32:49.970 --> 00:32:53.920
I'm going to turn it off and
just let the heat of the pan

00:32:53.920 --> 00:32:55.810
carry it the rest
of the way through.

00:32:55.810 --> 00:32:58.965
I am not worried at all that
that fish is going to overcook.

00:32:58.965 --> 00:32:59.877
Well, a little bit.

00:32:59.877 --> 00:33:00.460
But not a lot.

00:33:00.460 --> 00:33:01.140
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:01.640
OK.

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:03.760
So I'm going to bring
this up front here.

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:07.090
I'm going to crank this
up and turn that off.

00:33:07.090 --> 00:33:07.600
All right.

00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:09.058
Now I'm going to
just start shaking

00:33:09.058 --> 00:33:10.142
some butter into this pan.

00:33:10.142 --> 00:33:10.641
Right?

00:33:10.641 --> 00:33:12.930
This is called a "beurre
monte," or "mounted butter."

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:18.770
You just kind of-- you can
use a whisk, if you want.

00:33:18.770 --> 00:33:21.260
Shake the pan.

00:33:21.260 --> 00:33:24.230
Just making a real
simple emulsified butter.

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:31.690
I want more.

00:33:31.690 --> 00:33:33.930
One more butter.

00:33:33.930 --> 00:33:34.880
Butter's good.

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:37.540
Butter's not bad for you.

00:33:37.540 --> 00:33:38.120
It's not.

00:33:38.120 --> 00:33:39.280
Just ask Julia Child.

00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:40.760
Oh, she's dead.

00:33:40.760 --> 00:33:41.990
Sorry.

00:33:41.990 --> 00:33:44.120
Sorry, Julia!

00:33:44.120 --> 00:33:44.620
OK.

00:33:44.620 --> 00:33:45.760
I can hear that fish cooking.

00:33:45.760 --> 00:33:46.551
It's talking to me.

00:33:46.551 --> 00:33:48.080
It wants to come out of the pan.

00:33:48.080 --> 00:33:50.934
OK, yes, I hear you.

00:33:50.934 --> 00:33:52.600
And the funny thing
about it is, as soon

00:33:52.600 --> 00:33:54.683
as you flip over the fish,
the skin is not crispy.

00:33:54.683 --> 00:33:59.580
But once it gets a chance to
sit for a minute, I can hear it.

00:33:59.580 --> 00:34:01.840
It's kind of-- tick, tick,
tick, tick!-- crispy skin.

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:02.940
I like crispy skin.

00:34:02.940 --> 00:34:04.070
Delicious.

00:34:04.070 --> 00:34:05.810
Full of nutrition.

00:34:05.810 --> 00:34:09.389
Mostly the omega-3 fatty acids
that are so good for our brain,

00:34:09.389 --> 00:34:12.020
our body-- every
function of your body--

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:14.310
is located between the
skin and the flesh.

00:34:14.310 --> 00:34:16.690
So it's a little, thin layer,
there, generally speaking.

00:34:16.690 --> 00:34:20.629
So whenever possible,
whenever you're cool with it,

00:34:20.629 --> 00:34:22.219
eat the skin.

00:34:22.219 --> 00:34:23.120
Or consume the skin.

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:26.750
So I'm adding the lentils
to this beurre monte--

00:34:26.750 --> 00:34:28.164
this emulsified butter.

00:34:30.825 --> 00:34:32.969
It's basically just
reheating them.

00:34:32.969 --> 00:34:34.009
SHEILA BOWMAN: And sometimes
at the grocery store,

00:34:34.009 --> 00:34:36.340
you have to ask for fish
that still has the skin on.

00:34:36.340 --> 00:34:38.927
We're very much
into white fillets.

00:34:38.927 --> 00:34:41.510
But I know a lot of people are
starting to ask for that, Rick,

00:34:41.510 --> 00:34:45.940
because it's kind of fun
to cook and good flavor.

00:34:45.940 --> 00:34:48.330
RICK MOONEN: I'm 100%-- I've
been eating skin on fish

00:34:48.330 --> 00:34:48.830
forever.

00:34:48.830 --> 00:34:51.690
But not everybody-- I find
that plates come back,

00:34:51.690 --> 00:34:53.690
and the skin's been pulled
off nicely and placed

00:34:53.690 --> 00:34:54.739
onto the side.

00:34:54.739 --> 00:34:58.130
So I'm encouraging you to
step outside your comfort

00:34:58.130 --> 00:35:00.930
zone, maybe a little bit.

00:35:00.930 --> 00:35:03.240
So I'm putting down
this spicy, fiery

00:35:03.240 --> 00:35:05.500
hot-- we didn't do something
that's real important.

00:35:11.960 --> 00:35:13.150
Obviously tomato.

00:35:13.150 --> 00:35:14.500
It's got some good heat.

00:35:14.500 --> 00:35:16.830
Great acidity.

00:35:16.830 --> 00:35:18.700
Level of Moroccan spices?

00:35:18.700 --> 00:35:20.070
You know, what the heck?

00:35:20.070 --> 00:35:21.471
I'm feeling a little bit more.

00:35:21.471 --> 00:35:21.970
You know?

00:35:21.970 --> 00:35:23.060
Why not?

00:35:23.060 --> 00:35:24.680
I really want to
prove a point, here.

00:35:24.680 --> 00:35:26.430
I want you to
taste those spices.

00:35:26.430 --> 00:35:28.679
So put a little bit more.

00:35:28.679 --> 00:35:30.220
Push it down the
middle of the plate.

00:35:33.097 --> 00:35:34.430
This could be a little smoother.

00:35:34.430 --> 00:35:35.630
Doesn't matter.

00:35:35.630 --> 00:35:36.260
You know why?

00:35:36.260 --> 00:35:38.259
You just turn to people
and go, "That's rustic."

00:35:38.259 --> 00:35:40.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:40.270 --> 00:35:40.770
Right?

00:35:40.770 --> 00:35:45.130
And now we get our lentils.

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:46.550
Place them down the center.

00:35:46.550 --> 00:35:47.490
Nice and creamy.

00:35:52.529 --> 00:35:54.820
SHEILA BOWMAN: So I know
we're in the wrapping-up mode.

00:35:54.820 --> 00:35:57.200
We're going to do a few
questions here at the end.

00:35:57.200 --> 00:36:00.910
I know that the tastes are
coming along in the area

00:36:00.910 --> 00:36:02.470
directly behind us.

00:36:02.470 --> 00:36:03.570
Rick has a book.

00:36:03.570 --> 00:36:06.230
Is this recipe in the book?

00:36:06.230 --> 00:36:07.330
Or something like it?

00:36:07.330 --> 00:36:08.787
RICK MOONEN: Um-- I think so.

00:36:08.787 --> 00:36:09.870
Pretty sure it's in there.

00:36:09.870 --> 00:36:10.245
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:10.245 --> 00:36:11.078
SHEILA BOWMAN: Yeah.

00:36:11.078 --> 00:36:11.939
We think so.

00:36:11.939 --> 00:36:12.730
RICK MOONEN: It is.

00:36:12.730 --> 00:36:14.360
SHEILA BOWMAN: So
books will be on sale--

00:36:14.360 --> 00:36:16.443
RICK MOONEN: If it's not,
here's my business card.

00:36:16.443 --> 00:36:18.430
I'll be glad to send you
a copy of the recipe,

00:36:18.430 --> 00:36:19.950
if it's not available today.

00:36:19.950 --> 00:36:23.200
And then I put a little
cilantro on top, as a garnish,

00:36:23.200 --> 00:36:26.740
just to give it a little
bit of green color.

00:36:26.740 --> 00:36:28.800
And the cilantro
works really well.

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:31.600
Cilantro has a cooling
effect on your palate.

00:36:31.600 --> 00:36:34.850
Whenever you see something
spicy such as guacamole, salsa,

00:36:34.850 --> 00:36:38.870
all that-- that's the reason
cilantro works so well.

00:36:38.870 --> 00:36:41.480
And you know what?

00:36:41.480 --> 00:36:43.900
It's cilantro two ways, if
you really think about it.

00:36:43.900 --> 00:36:45.615
Because in the
Moroccan spice mix

00:36:45.615 --> 00:36:49.310
is coriander, which is the
seed that made the cilantro

00:36:49.310 --> 00:36:50.630
in the first place.

00:36:50.630 --> 00:36:52.877
So there you have a
super simple dish.

00:36:52.877 --> 00:36:55.460
A discussion, maybe, of a little
bit of a better understanding

00:36:55.460 --> 00:36:56.817
about aquaculture.

00:36:56.817 --> 00:36:58.400
"You know, I went
into that room today

00:36:58.400 --> 00:37:00.090
thinking aquaculture was bad."

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:03.070
It's not as bad
as it used to be.

00:37:03.070 --> 00:37:05.220
There are people that
are doing a great job.

00:37:05.220 --> 00:37:07.250
There's people that are
doing a much better job.

00:37:07.250 --> 00:37:10.030
And there's some people that
are still doing an OK job.

00:37:10.030 --> 00:37:14.290
So what I try to do to
celebrate the great,

00:37:14.290 --> 00:37:17.455
recognize the better,
encouraging them to be great,

00:37:17.455 --> 00:37:19.330
and hoping that the guys
that aren't doing it

00:37:19.330 --> 00:37:20.705
so well either go
out of business

00:37:20.705 --> 00:37:22.250
or figure out and
go back on board.

00:37:22.250 --> 00:37:24.940
And then we have
widespread solutions

00:37:24.940 --> 00:37:26.960
that are pushing us
in the right direction

00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:29.020
to a more sustainable world.

00:37:29.020 --> 00:37:30.900
We're not eradicating species.

00:37:30.900 --> 00:37:32.300
We're closer to our food.

00:37:32.300 --> 00:37:34.140
We have a better understanding.

00:37:34.140 --> 00:37:35.980
I mean, the discussion
can go on forever.

00:37:35.980 --> 00:37:37.200
I mean, it's--

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:38.920
And when it's
wild, see-- there's

00:37:38.920 --> 00:37:41.190
overfishing, because
that's technology's ability

00:37:41.190 --> 00:37:45.150
to out-fish a species.

00:37:45.150 --> 00:37:46.660
They can't keep
up with the hunt.

00:37:46.660 --> 00:37:48.804
There's byproducts-- the
by-catch that comes up.

00:37:48.804 --> 00:37:51.220
When they're going after one
targeted species in the wild,

00:37:51.220 --> 00:37:54.900
other stuff comes up with
it that we're not really

00:37:54.900 --> 00:37:55.420
targeting.

00:37:55.420 --> 00:37:57.822
So by the time you filter
out everything you wanted,

00:37:57.822 --> 00:37:59.030
those fish are dead or dying.

00:37:59.030 --> 00:38:00.529
They get pushed
back into the ocean.

00:38:00.529 --> 00:38:01.222
What a waste.

00:38:01.222 --> 00:38:02.430
What a waste of good protein.

00:38:02.430 --> 00:38:05.380
There's aquaculture, the effect
that it has on the environment,

00:38:05.380 --> 00:38:07.510
and the effect that it
has on the fish itself.

00:38:07.510 --> 00:38:08.870
The fish itself.

00:38:08.870 --> 00:38:09.940
Antibiotics.

00:38:09.940 --> 00:38:10.850
Chemicals.

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:12.460
You know, all the
things that need

00:38:12.460 --> 00:38:15.380
to be added in order to keep it
a healthy and viable investment

00:38:15.380 --> 00:38:17.750
for an aquaculture owner.

00:38:17.750 --> 00:38:19.980
But there's also
the environment.

00:38:19.980 --> 00:38:20.870
The byproduct.

00:38:20.870 --> 00:38:21.480
The effluent.

00:38:21.480 --> 00:38:22.150
The escapes.

00:38:22.150 --> 00:38:23.057
The fish around it.

00:38:23.057 --> 00:38:25.640
All the other things that need
to be taken into consideration.

00:38:25.640 --> 00:38:26.639
You think, like, really?

00:38:26.639 --> 00:38:30.180
Aren't we exhausting this to--
we're beating a dead horse.

00:38:30.180 --> 00:38:33.400
Does it really have that
much of an effect on a world

00:38:33.400 --> 00:38:36.390
that two thirds of it
plus is covered in water?

00:38:36.390 --> 00:38:37.310
Yes, it is.

00:38:37.310 --> 00:38:38.470
Yes, it does.

00:38:38.470 --> 00:38:39.780
It has a major effect.

00:38:39.780 --> 00:38:42.590
We've treated our oceans as our
receptacle for way too long,

00:38:42.590 --> 00:38:44.710
expecting perfect food
to come out of it.

00:38:44.710 --> 00:38:47.399
Because you can't just
dump all of the junk

00:38:47.399 --> 00:38:49.690
that you don't want to deal
with on land into the ocean

00:38:49.690 --> 00:38:51.970
and think that it's going
to come out pristine.

00:38:51.970 --> 00:38:55.230
So all back, circle
around, put your toys away

00:38:55.230 --> 00:38:56.390
at the end of the night.

00:38:56.390 --> 00:38:57.656
Put them back in the box.

00:38:57.656 --> 00:38:58.780
Put them back on the shelf.

00:38:58.780 --> 00:38:59.800
Next day, you take them down.

00:38:59.800 --> 00:39:00.740
They're perfect again.

00:39:00.740 --> 00:39:03.010
And you can enjoy
great-tasting food.

00:39:03.010 --> 00:39:03.810
All right?

00:39:03.810 --> 00:39:05.851
SHEILA BOWMAN: So Rick,
how do you choose seafood

00:39:05.851 --> 00:39:07.669
that you serve and eat?

00:39:07.669 --> 00:39:09.210
RICK MOONEN: How do
I choose seafood?

00:39:09.210 --> 00:39:10.950
I use Seafood Watch,
generally speaking,

00:39:10.950 --> 00:39:12.460
as my-- I-- here we go.

00:39:12.460 --> 00:39:13.080
Look at this.

00:39:13.080 --> 00:39:14.009
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:14.009 --> 00:39:15.800
SHEILA BOWMAN: That
was a leading question.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:17.383
RICK MOONEN: I had
a feeling that was.

00:39:17.383 --> 00:39:18.897
No, this is the beauty of it.

00:39:18.897 --> 00:39:20.730
Seafood Watch-- there's
these little cards--

00:39:20.730 --> 00:39:22.450
and outside there's a display.

00:39:22.450 --> 00:39:23.810
Please come out and pick one up.

00:39:23.810 --> 00:39:24.726
Put it in your wallet.

00:39:24.726 --> 00:39:25.440
Talk about it.

00:39:25.440 --> 00:39:26.440
It's super simple.

00:39:26.440 --> 00:39:27.060
Seafood Watch.

00:39:27.060 --> 00:39:30.840
What they do is they have
three categories-- red, orange,

00:39:30.840 --> 00:39:31.590
and green.

00:39:31.590 --> 00:39:34.900
Green means "best
choice; go for it."

00:39:34.900 --> 00:39:37.650
And guess who's done all
the research on overfishing,

00:39:37.650 --> 00:39:41.580
habitat destruction, byproduct--
I mean, by-catch, and all that?

00:39:41.580 --> 00:39:42.470
Monterey Bay has.

00:39:42.470 --> 00:39:44.860
Because they've got
an incredible network

00:39:44.860 --> 00:39:48.190
of connections to scientists,
to environmentalists,

00:39:48.190 --> 00:39:51.430
to government
organizations, both non-

00:39:51.430 --> 00:39:52.960
and government organizations.

00:39:52.960 --> 00:39:56.850
All of it gets boiled down
to a red, green, and yellow.

00:39:56.850 --> 00:39:59.995
So, green-- you can't get
green, but ask for it.

00:39:59.995 --> 00:40:02.120
Yellow's OK, but there's
still some issues with it.

00:40:02.120 --> 00:40:04.410
But it's a better
choice than the red.

00:40:04.410 --> 00:40:07.310
The red means
[BUZZER SOUND] "avoid.

00:40:07.310 --> 00:40:08.330
Avoid, for now."

00:40:08.330 --> 00:40:09.930
What do you mean "for now?"

00:40:09.930 --> 00:40:11.100
That's why you have an app.

00:40:11.100 --> 00:40:12.910
Because at any given
moment, it could change.

00:40:12.910 --> 00:40:13.420
Tomorrow.

00:40:13.420 --> 00:40:15.350
So you just push
in on-- you search

00:40:15.350 --> 00:40:16.660
for "seafood" or "sushi."

00:40:16.660 --> 00:40:17.660
You push on that.

00:40:17.660 --> 00:40:18.750
You put in your species.

00:40:18.750 --> 00:40:22.270
I punch in "trout."
(MUMBLING) T-R-O-U-T.

00:40:22.270 --> 00:40:25.590
It's going to tell me
"Don't serve it at Google."

00:40:25.590 --> 00:40:26.090
No.

00:40:26.090 --> 00:40:26.589
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:26.589 --> 00:40:29.570
It's going to say "best
choice." "Best choice."

00:40:29.570 --> 00:40:32.020
Basically, trout is
a pretty-- doesn't

00:40:32.020 --> 00:40:33.224
leave a heavy footprint.

00:40:33.224 --> 00:40:33.890
It's affordable.

00:40:33.890 --> 00:40:34.707
It's delicious.

00:40:34.707 --> 00:40:36.790
You're about to have a
little bit of a taste of it

00:40:36.790 --> 00:40:38.420
as soon as we're
finished over here.

00:40:38.420 --> 00:40:41.900
But while that's happening,
download Seafood Watch.

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:43.150
It's a free app.

00:40:43.150 --> 00:40:44.240
Why not?

00:40:44.240 --> 00:40:44.980
You know?

00:40:44.980 --> 00:40:46.605
It's one more cool
thing on your phone,

00:40:46.605 --> 00:40:48.260
as you go down the
50 pages of stuff

00:40:48.260 --> 00:40:49.200
you got on there, probably.

00:40:49.200 --> 00:40:49.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:49.700 --> 00:40:54.891
But, you know, I've been
talking about this for decades.

00:40:54.891 --> 00:40:56.890
In the beginning, it
certainly wasn't very cool.

00:40:56.890 --> 00:40:57.950
People were, like,
oh, Moonen, really?

00:40:57.950 --> 00:40:58.560
What the hell, now?

00:40:58.560 --> 00:41:00.140
You're going to make me take
something else off of my menu?

00:41:00.140 --> 00:41:01.080
You're gonna--

00:41:01.080 --> 00:41:02.650
It's not that complicated.

00:41:02.650 --> 00:41:04.290
It doesn't need to
be that complicated.

00:41:04.290 --> 00:41:06.030
You know, when you go
into a gas station,

00:41:06.030 --> 00:41:07.970
you're sort of picky
about your octane level,

00:41:07.970 --> 00:41:09.140
because you don't want
to mess up your motor.

00:41:09.140 --> 00:41:10.770
You know, you pick
the right thing.

00:41:10.770 --> 00:41:12.530
Pick the right thing here.

00:41:12.530 --> 00:41:13.120
You know?

00:41:13.120 --> 00:41:15.510
And food is what
connects us all.

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:18.110
It's the common language
of the entire world.

00:41:18.110 --> 00:41:21.860
No matter where I go, I
have a conversation going.

00:41:21.860 --> 00:41:22.517
I'm in Greece.

00:41:22.517 --> 00:41:23.600
I'm talking about octopus.

00:41:23.600 --> 00:41:24.760
How do you cook octopus?

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:26.218
Oh, well-- Next
thing you know, you

00:41:26.218 --> 00:41:28.800
get a 20-minute conversation
going on with a cab driver.

00:41:28.800 --> 00:41:33.100
So it's really what
makes us who we are.

00:41:33.100 --> 00:41:38.560
And it's-- I've seen, over my
35-plus-year career, thus far,

00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:41.970
so many changes-- so
many positive changes.

00:41:41.970 --> 00:41:46.460
But we're at a critical
state as we grow as a planet.

00:41:46.460 --> 00:41:51.810
And too many generations
have distanced themselves

00:41:51.810 --> 00:41:54.669
from-- where's the
food coming from?

00:41:54.669 --> 00:41:55.710
Is it really good for me?

00:41:55.710 --> 00:41:56.960
Is it good for my family?

00:41:56.960 --> 00:41:59.200
Is it going to make
me feel better?

00:41:59.200 --> 00:42:00.510
Does it taste good?

00:42:00.510 --> 00:42:01.010
All right?

00:42:01.010 --> 00:42:04.020
And I'm a proponent of
all of those things.

00:42:04.020 --> 00:42:05.760
For some reason,
early on in my career,

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:07.470
it was instilled within me.

00:42:07.470 --> 00:42:08.890
Download the app.

00:42:08.890 --> 00:42:10.100
Become a know-it-all.

00:42:10.100 --> 00:42:11.230
Ask questions.

00:42:11.230 --> 00:42:12.970
Please ask questions.

00:42:12.970 --> 00:42:15.380
When you stand up to that
fish counter, I guarantee,

00:42:15.380 --> 00:42:17.350
if you have your app
open, you already

00:42:17.350 --> 00:42:19.510
know more than maybe the
guy behind the counter.

00:42:19.510 --> 00:42:21.121
Hey-- where's it from?

00:42:21.121 --> 00:42:21.620
You know?

00:42:21.620 --> 00:42:22.820
And then you'll start
to learn a little bit

00:42:22.820 --> 00:42:24.570
about other acronyms of life.

00:42:24.570 --> 00:42:26.350
There's millions of
them in this world.

00:42:26.350 --> 00:42:27.470
They'll drive you crazy.

00:42:27.470 --> 00:42:30.960
MSC is one good one--
Marine Stewardship Council.

00:42:30.960 --> 00:42:33.010
Pretty much, if it has
an MSC label on it,

00:42:33.010 --> 00:42:35.630
it had to go through this
incredibly rigorous, almost

00:42:35.630 --> 00:42:39.900
torturous selection process
to get them to be approved.

00:42:39.900 --> 00:42:43.560
So that's usually a pretty
sound, sustainable choice,

00:42:43.560 --> 00:42:45.260
when something has MSC on it.

00:42:45.260 --> 00:42:48.537
But if you look for the green,
you're doing an amazing job.

00:42:48.537 --> 00:42:50.870
You go for yellow, no one's
going to really yell at you,

00:42:50.870 --> 00:42:52.430
but keep trying for the green.

00:42:52.430 --> 00:42:54.190
Does that answer your question?

00:42:54.190 --> 00:42:55.080
SHEILA BOWMAN: That
was a great answer.

00:42:55.080 --> 00:42:55.580
RICK MOONEN: What a lead-up.

00:42:55.580 --> 00:42:56.220
What a lead-up.

00:42:56.220 --> 00:42:57.845
AUDIENCE: We have a
question over here,

00:42:57.845 --> 00:42:59.850
so if you want to help me--

00:42:59.850 --> 00:43:01.800
AUDIENCE: I think it
was the "LA Times" had

00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:05.630
an article about how mislabeled
fish was in restaurants.

00:43:05.630 --> 00:43:08.900
When they did the DNA
testing, it was often wrong.

00:43:08.900 --> 00:43:11.530
Do you think that
was-- part of the chef?

00:43:11.530 --> 00:43:13.820
Part of the suppliers?

00:43:13.820 --> 00:43:15.881
RICK MOONEN: Well, it's
a combination of both.

00:43:15.881 --> 00:43:17.630
And it's a great
question, because I'm not

00:43:17.630 --> 00:43:18.580
going to shirk my
responsibilities

00:43:18.580 --> 00:43:20.285
and say as chefs,
it's not our job.

00:43:20.285 --> 00:43:21.640
It's the purveyors' job.

00:43:21.640 --> 00:43:22.590
It is our job.

00:43:22.590 --> 00:43:23.480
It's our job to know.

00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:24.320
It's our job to ask.

00:43:24.320 --> 00:43:26.410
It's our job to doubt.

00:43:26.410 --> 00:43:28.010
And especially because of that.

00:43:28.010 --> 00:43:29.280
Great point, actually.

00:43:29.280 --> 00:43:31.220
Most fish are mislabeled.

00:43:31.220 --> 00:43:32.679
Why?

00:43:32.679 --> 00:43:34.095
The darned stuff's
pretty darned--

00:43:34.095 --> 00:43:35.940
it's pretty perishable.

00:43:35.940 --> 00:43:37.566
It's the most
perishable inventory

00:43:37.566 --> 00:43:39.690
you're going to ever try
to deal with in your life.

00:43:39.690 --> 00:43:41.310
I decided, why not?

00:43:41.310 --> 00:43:43.276
I'll deal with the
hardest-to-keep products.

00:43:43.276 --> 00:43:44.400
And it's like a hot potato.

00:43:44.400 --> 00:43:45.090
You've got to get rid of it.

00:43:45.090 --> 00:43:46.410
Otherwise, it's not
going to be as good.

00:43:46.410 --> 00:43:48.201
And I'll do it in the
desert, in the middle

00:43:48.201 --> 00:43:49.857
of Las Vegas, Nevada.

00:43:49.857 --> 00:43:51.690
And talk about
sustainability, as a message.

00:43:51.690 --> 00:43:52.250
Why not?

00:43:52.250 --> 00:43:53.680
I like the challenge.

00:43:53.680 --> 00:43:55.570
So yeah.

00:43:55.570 --> 00:43:58.617
If I'm a purveyor,
and I've got the phone

00:43:58.617 --> 00:44:00.450
call from Rick Moonen
going, "Listen, buddy,

00:44:00.450 --> 00:44:02.330
I need swordfish.

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:05.990
But I need harpooned
swordfish, because it's

00:44:05.990 --> 00:44:08.940
the most sustainable method
of going after swordfish."

00:44:08.940 --> 00:44:10.950
And the guy's going to
go "How much do you need?

00:44:10.950 --> 00:44:12.560
40 pounds!

00:44:12.560 --> 00:44:13.560
Put a hole in that fish.

00:44:13.560 --> 00:44:15.570
Make it look like it was a
swordfish that got harpooned.

00:44:15.570 --> 00:44:16.778
Yeah, we got harpooned fish!"

00:44:16.778 --> 00:44:18.336
They'll sell it to
you all day long.

00:44:18.336 --> 00:44:19.710
You have to trust
your purveyors.

00:44:19.710 --> 00:44:22.090
You have to trust your
sources, as a chef.

00:44:22.090 --> 00:44:25.950
As a consumer going
into a restaurant,

00:44:25.950 --> 00:44:29.550
or a consumer going into a
marketplace, open up your app.

00:44:29.550 --> 00:44:30.560
Be a know-it-all.

00:44:30.560 --> 00:44:31.940
Please be a know-it-all.

00:44:31.940 --> 00:44:32.870
Be a pain in the neck.

00:44:32.870 --> 00:44:34.078
Mention my name, if you want.

00:44:34.078 --> 00:44:35.140
I don't care.

00:44:35.140 --> 00:44:37.570
Use me as the bad guy,
because it's not being bad.

00:44:37.570 --> 00:44:39.180
Because you're doing something
good for the environment

00:44:39.180 --> 00:44:39.770
and yourself.

00:44:39.770 --> 00:44:43.160
So it's a win-win situation
when you ask questions.

00:44:43.160 --> 00:44:46.646
AUDIENCE: Are there any labels
to avoid or specifically

00:44:46.646 --> 00:44:48.640
look for when you're
in the grocery store?

00:44:48.640 --> 00:44:50.920
RICK MOONEN: Labels to avoid.

00:44:50.920 --> 00:44:51.550
Hmm.

00:44:51.550 --> 00:44:53.150
Sheila?

00:44:53.150 --> 00:44:55.050
Do you have an answer to that?

00:44:55.050 --> 00:44:57.920
I don't want to say-- you know--
there's certain countries that

00:44:57.920 --> 00:44:58.530
do--

00:44:58.530 --> 00:45:01.970
SHEILA BOWMAN: Well, I think, to
answer your question, you know,

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:03.940
everyone's sustainable
out there today.

00:45:03.940 --> 00:45:04.650
Everyone.

00:45:04.650 --> 00:45:07.720
So you talk to a purveyor,
and he goes "Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:45:07.720 --> 00:45:09.810
It's sustainable trout."

00:45:09.810 --> 00:45:13.115
So if you're getting that
line, it kind of is a line.

00:45:13.115 --> 00:45:15.060
And a lot of our chefs
are, like-- you know,

00:45:15.060 --> 00:45:17.080
these suppliers can be
like used-car salesmen.

00:45:17.080 --> 00:45:18.980
It's like-- yeah,
yeah, yeah, yeah!

00:45:18.980 --> 00:45:21.220
It's-- where did
you want it from?

00:45:21.220 --> 00:45:21.720
Idaho?

00:45:21.720 --> 00:45:22.570
Yeah.

00:45:22.570 --> 00:45:23.070
Yeah!

00:45:23.070 --> 00:45:24.361
RICK MOONEN: That's the ticket!

00:45:24.361 --> 00:45:25.170
Sure!

00:45:25.170 --> 00:45:26.830
SHEILA BOWMAN: So
I think what you're

00:45:26.830 --> 00:45:28.700
sort of looking at
is, if anyone just

00:45:28.700 --> 00:45:31.160
says "sustainable,"
I'm always like-- OK,

00:45:31.160 --> 00:45:32.709
they should have
more behind that.

00:45:32.709 --> 00:45:34.500
They should be able to
say where it's from.

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:35.210
How it was cut.

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:37.920
What sustainable?

00:45:37.920 --> 00:45:40.080
So I think the one I
would most worry about

00:45:40.080 --> 00:45:42.420
is this, like, "yeah,
yeah, it's sustainable."

00:45:42.420 --> 00:45:43.970
That's what I would worry about.

00:45:43.970 --> 00:45:45.810
If you don't have
anything to back it up,

00:45:45.810 --> 00:45:49.220
then you're-- that's what
asking questions will do--

00:45:49.220 --> 00:45:50.270
add that accountability.

00:45:50.270 --> 00:45:51.770
RICK MOONEN: Great
question, though.

00:45:51.770 --> 00:45:54.160
Really, there's
no easy solution.

00:45:54.160 --> 00:45:55.194
There's no easy answer.

00:45:55.194 --> 00:45:56.610
Hopefully, someday,
there will be.

00:45:56.610 --> 00:45:57.545
I doubt it.

00:45:57.545 --> 00:45:58.920
You're just going
to have to know

00:45:58.920 --> 00:45:59.680
where your food comes from.

00:45:59.680 --> 00:46:01.020
You're going to have to have
a little bit more knowledge.

00:46:01.020 --> 00:46:01.990
And it's fun.

00:46:01.990 --> 00:46:03.120
Make it fun.

00:46:03.120 --> 00:46:04.500
Don't make it a drudgery.

00:46:04.500 --> 00:46:05.290
Yes.

00:46:05.290 --> 00:46:05.670
AUDIENCE: Thank you, chef.

00:46:05.670 --> 00:46:07.730
So what are some of your
favorites from the green list

00:46:07.730 --> 00:46:09.670
that you think that maybe
we haven't cooked with,

00:46:09.670 --> 00:46:11.550
or we haven't tried, that you
would want to recommend to us?

00:46:11.550 --> 00:46:13.402
RICK MOONEN: Do you
have a green list handy?

00:46:13.402 --> 00:46:14.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:14.620 --> 00:46:18.300
No, but he's asking
for my favorites.

00:46:18.300 --> 00:46:21.830
I love lower-- if you eat lower
on the food chain-- generally

00:46:21.830 --> 00:46:25.810
speaking, smaller fish-- you're
doing yourself a world of good.

00:46:25.810 --> 00:46:27.390
Because they're fast-growing.

00:46:27.390 --> 00:46:31.020
They don't have any
health concerns or issues.

00:46:31.020 --> 00:46:32.615
PCBs, Methylmercury--

00:46:32.615 --> 00:46:33.740
SHEILA BOWMAN: Arctic char.

00:46:33.740 --> 00:46:34.781
RICK MOONEN: Arctic char.

00:46:34.781 --> 00:46:35.780
I love Arctic char.

00:46:35.780 --> 00:46:40.179
Arctic char is, categorically,
in the trout and salmon family.

00:46:40.179 --> 00:46:42.220
So trout and salmon are
really-- they're cousins.

00:46:42.220 --> 00:46:43.284
So it's all good stuff.

00:46:43.284 --> 00:46:44.450
SHEILA BOWMAN: Striped bass?

00:46:44.450 --> 00:46:46.460
RICK MOONEN: Striped
bass from the East Coast.

00:46:46.460 --> 00:46:47.850
We're on the West
Coast, so you're not

00:46:47.850 --> 00:46:48.830
going to see a lot of that.

00:46:48.830 --> 00:46:49.480
SHEILA BOWMAN: Sturgeon?

00:46:49.480 --> 00:46:50.230
RICK MOONEN: Wait!

00:46:50.230 --> 00:46:52.125
But striped bass, also
known as rockfish--

00:46:52.125 --> 00:46:53.110
SHEILA BOWMAN: On
the East Coast.

00:46:53.110 --> 00:46:54.485
RICK MOONEN: --on
the East Coast.

00:46:54.485 --> 00:46:56.950
Rockfish on the West
Coast suddenly--

00:46:56.950 --> 00:47:02.680
not suddenly, but recently--
became a sustainable category.

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:03.360
Holy smokes.

